00:54:49,328 --> 00:54:51,205
Some old items from Rodriguez.

869
00:54:54,708 --> 00:54:59,805
This is his bumper sticker, from
the first time he ran for city council.

870
00:55:02,132 --> 00:55:05,352
And I think this is a copy
of the ballot.

871
00:55:05,803 --> 00:55:08,101
He didn't win an election, ever.

872
00:55:08,388 --> 00:55:13,690
139. There were 169 candidates.
Nine get elected.

873
00:55:14,645 --> 00:55:17,114
They spelled his name wrong.

874
00:55:25,155 --> 00:55:30,878
My relatives on my mother's side
of the family are European

875
00:55:31,495 --> 00:55:33,372
and Native American.

876
00:55:33,497 --> 00:55:36,216
And my father's family is Mexican.

877
00:55:36,291 --> 00:55:38,919
My grandfather came from Mexico.

878
00:55:38,919 --> 00:55:43,140
<i>The Mexican came to Detroit
to work in the auto factories,</i>

879
00:55:43,215 --> 00:55:48,893
<i>so we were working-class people,
blue-collar workers, hard labor.</i>

880
00:55:49,513 --> 00:55:55,065
<i>Um, we lived in 26 different homes
and some houses didn't have bedrooms.</i>

881
00:55:55,143 --> 00:55:57,362
<i>Some houses didn't have bathrooms.</i>

882
00:55:57,938 --> 00:56:02,068
<i>And they weren't homes.
They were just places that we lived.</i>

883
00:56:02,609 --> 00:56:06,455
But just because people are poor
or have little

884
00:56:07,114 --> 00:56:10,368
doesn't mean that, you know,
their dreams aren't big

885
00:56:10,450 --> 00:56:13,624
and their soul isn't rich, you know,

886
00:56:14,162 --> 00:56:18,087
and that's where the classes
and the prejudice come from

887
00:56:18,166 --> 00:56:20,669
is that there is a difference
between you and me,

888
00:56:20,752 --> 00:56:22,595
and there's a difference
between them and us.

889
00:56:23,714 --> 00:56:25,136
(# <i>A Most Disgusting Song</i> by Rodriguez)

890
00:56:25,215 --> 00:56:28,560
# <i>I've played every kind of gig
there is to play now</i>

891
00:56:30,888 --> 00:56:35,064
# <i>I've played faggot bars, hooker bars,
motorcycle funerals</i>

892
00:56:36,268 --> 00:56:40,614
# <i>In opera houses, concert halls,
halfway houses</i>

893
00:56:47,070 --> 00:56:50,700
# <i>Well, I found that in all these places
that I've played</i>

894
00:56:52,659 --> 00:56:56,209
# <i>All the people that I've played for
are the same people</i>

895
00:56:57,873 --> 00:57:02,003
# <i>So if you'll listen, maybe you'll see
someone you know in this song</i>

896
00:57:03,295 --> 00:57:05,514
# <i>A most disgusting song</i>

897
00:57:07,883 --> 00:57:10,261
(Regan) He wasn't just doing
your average carpentry, you know,

898
00:57:10,344 --> 00:57:13,018
he was really cleaning out the house.

899
00:57:13,096 --> 00:57:15,895
I mean, doing work that no one else
wanted to do.

900
00:57:16,725 --> 00:57:19,228
Really, no one else
wanted to do that work.

901
00:57:19,311 --> 00:57:25,239
<i>He would come home, he would be
covered in dust and dirt, paint chips,

902
00:57:25,484 --> 00:57:28,613
<i>from his day's work. Long days.</i>

903
00:57:29,154 --> 00:57:33,910
<i>I saw him take refrigerators
down on his back, downstairs.</i>

904
00:57:34,826 --> 00:57:36,703
It was just a day at work for him,

905
00:57:36,787 --> 00:57:41,418
but I knew he was a harder worker than
a lot of other fathers that I knew of.

906
00:57:42,751 --> 00:57:45,220
<i>(Sandra Rodriguez-Kennedy) It's a city
that tells you not to dream big,</i>

907
00:57:45,295 --> 00:57:48,094
<i>not to expect anything more.</i>

908
00:57:48,173 --> 00:57:50,642
<i>But he always took me to places</i>

909
00:57:50,717 --> 00:57:54,096
<i>that only certain elite people
would be able to go.</i>

910
00:57:55,305 --> 00:57:57,649
So, he kind of instilled in me
that I can go anywhere I want,

911
00:57:57,724 --> 00:58:02,480
regardless of what my bank statement
says, and I'm going, you know.

912
00:58:03,063 --> 00:58:07,819
So, that's kinda how he was.
He showed me the top floors of places.

913
00:58:07,901 --> 00:58:10,825
<i>I said, "I'm just as good as they are,"
you know.</i>

914
00:58:10,904 --> 00:58:14,033
<i>(Eva) He majored in philosophy
in university.</i>

915
00:58:14,866 --> 00:58:18,496
<i>My dad gave us a lot of exposure
to the arts.</i>

916
00:58:18,578 --> 00:58:24,176
<i>He would let us go into the libraries and
the museums and the science centres,</i>

917
00:58:24,251 --> 00:58:27,004
and where that was our day care,

918
00:58:28,422 --> 00:58:32,928
and we toured the halls of the museum
in San Diego Rivera

919
00:58:33,010 --> 00:58:37,311
and, you know,
all Picasso and Delacroix and...

920
00:58:37,389 --> 00:58:41,189
We began to learn of life
outside of the city,

921
00:58:41,268 --> 00:58:43,942
and that's in books and paintings
and in music.

922
00:58:44,021 --> 00:58:45,398
(# <i>Lifestyles</i> by Rodriguez)

923
00:58:45,480 --> 00:58:48,199
# <i>The judges with meter-maid hearts</i>

924
00:58:48,275 --> 00:58:51,404
# <i>Or their supermarket justice starts</i>

925
00:58:52,446 --> 00:58:55,450
# <i>Frozen children inner city</i>

926
00:58:58,076 --> 00:59:00,420
# <i>Walkers in the paper rain</i>

927
00:59:00,495 --> 00:59:03,544
# <i>Waiting for those knights
that never came</i>

928
00:59:04,833 --> 00:59:08,212
# <i>The hijacked
trying so hard to be pretty</i>

929
00:59:10,547 --> 00:59:14,268
# <i>Night rains tap at my window</i>

930
00:59:16,720 --> 00:59:20,475
# <i>Winds of my thoughts passing by</i>

931
00:59:23,060 --> 00:59:27,065
# <i>She laughed when I tried to tell her</i>

932
00:59:29,399 --> 00:59:33,154
# <i>Hello only ends in goodbye</i>

933
00:59:56,843 --> 00:59:58,845
(Rodriguez) Well, I started playing
when I was 16,

934
00:59:58,845 --> 01:00:01,849
and the thing is,
it was a family guitar,

935
01:00:01,932 --> 01:00:07,029
and I played a lot of bars in the city
and clubs in the city, small rooms.

936
01:00:08,522 --> 01:00:11,446
And I met Mike Theodore
and Dennis Coffey

937
01:00:11,525 --> 01:00:14,028
and they came to the club
to see me play.

938
01:00:14,152 --> 01:00:18,032
I had a gig at a place called The Sewer,

939
01:00:18,532 --> 01:00:20,660
right out by the Detroit River,

940
01:00:20,784 --> 01:00:24,459
and then we got a record deal
from Clarence Avant,

941
01:00:24,538 --> 01:00:26,211
so that's how it started.

942
01:00:26,331 --> 01:00:30,131
<i>But all those early years were,</i>
<i>you know... lot of work.</i>

943
01:00:30,877 --> 01:00:34,552
<i>I was at a Chrysler plant
called Dodge Maine,</i>

944
01:00:34,631 --> 01:00:37,680
<i>and I also worked
at Eldon and Lynch Road in Detroit.</i>

945
01:00:37,801 --> 01:00:41,180
<i>Worked in the heat treat department.
Stuff like that.</i>

946
01:00:41,179 --> 01:00:43,181
<i>A lot of heavy labor.</i>

947
01:00:43,181 --> 01:00:47,186
<i>But it was a good year for me.
This</i> Cold Fact <i>thing.</i>

948
01:00:48,145 --> 01:00:52,400
<i>I had achieved what I was trying to do,
is to get a product, you know.</i>

949
01:00:52,524 --> 01:00:55,198
<i>And it was going very well,
I thought, you know.</i>

950
01:00:55,193 --> 01:01:00,415
<i>How did it feel? A great feeling
of accomplishment. Actualization.</i>

951
01:01:01,074 --> 01:01:03,202
<i>(male interviewer) Did you believe
that it was a good album?</i>

952
01:01:03,201 --> 01:01:04,703
<i>(Rodriguez) Um...</i>

953
01:01:04,828 --> 01:01:07,047
I did my best with it.

954
01:01:09,082 --> 01:01:11,710
The reviews were good on it, and...

955
01:01:12,669 --> 01:01:14,842
Yeah, I thought it was good.

956
01:01:16,923 --> 01:01:20,018
I'm not the one to ask that, though.
(chuckles)

957
01:01:20,093 --> 01:01:21,936
Ask that question to.

958
01:01:22,053 --> 01:01:23,600
But you go ahead, yeah.

959
01:01:23,680 --> 01:01:25,432
<i>Were you surprised that it didn't sell?

960
01:01:25,515 --> 01:01:26,937
Um...

961
01:01:28,101 --> 01:01:33,949
Was I surprised? It's the music business
so there's no guarantees, you know?

962
01:01:39,946 --> 01:01:42,290
<i>(Segerman) So I told him,
"You're bigger than Elvis,"</i>

963
01:01:42,282 --> 01:01:43,875
<i>and he said, "What do you mean?"</i>

964
01:01:43,950 --> 01:01:47,625
<i>I said, "In South Africa you are
more popular than Elvis Presley".</i>

965
01:01:47,704 --> 01:01:49,126
<i>And there was this pause,

966
01:01:49,247 --> 01:01:52,296
and I sensed he thought it was
a crank call and he was gonna hang up.

967
01:01:52,375 --> 01:01:55,754
So I said, "Listen, wait.
Listen, listen to me, wait.

968
01:01:55,879 --> 01:01:58,632
"I promise you, just come here.
You won't be disappointed".

969
01:01:59,090 --> 01:02:01,969
<i>(Emmerson)
He's working his ass off in Woodbridge.</i>

970
01:02:01,968 --> 01:02:05,643
One day, be brought this picture
of himself on a milk carton.

971
01:02:05,722 --> 01:02:07,816
(chuckles)

972
01:02:07,933 --> 01:02:12,609
And he'd say, "Emmerson, look at this.
You know, they're looking for me".

973
01:02:14,397 --> 01:02:17,992
I said,
"Really? Why is that, Rodriguez?"

974
01:02:18,902 --> 01:02:22,076
<i>Next day he says,
"Emmerson, I gotta go on tour".</i>

975
01:02:22,656 --> 01:02:25,000
<i>I said, "Come on, Rodriguez,</i>
<i>are you serious?"</i>

976
01:02:25,116 --> 01:02:26,993
<i>(Rian Malan) Because I'm a journalist,
I doubted it.</i>

977
01:02:26,993 --> 01:02:29,917
<i>That sort of thing does not happen
in the rational universe.</i>

978
01:02:29,996 --> 01:02:32,840
<i>It does not happen.
It's against the laws of God and nature.</i>

979
01:02:32,958 --> 01:02:35,336
<i>This guy is coming to tour here,
he must be an imposter.</i>

980
01:02:35,335 --> 01:02:38,179
It's a clever public relations scam.

981
01:02:38,171 --> 01:02:41,801
Actually, not even a clever
public relations scam. It's a stupid...

982
01:02:41,883 --> 01:02:46,389
'Cause it so obviously can't be true.
Only idiots would believe it. They...

983
01:02:48,556 --> 01:02:50,183
But I was wrong.

984
01:02:58,400 --> 01:03:00,528
<i>(Regan) We were always anxious,
of course, to get off the plane.</i>

985
01:03:00,527 --> 01:03:02,074
<i>That was a long flight.</i>

986
01:03:02,070 --> 01:03:05,700
But we got off the plane
and we put our bags on our backs

987
01:03:05,699 --> 01:03:11,081
and, you know, they were heavy and
we just kept moving towards the airport.

988
01:03:12,080 --> 01:03:15,584
And suddenly,
three, two limousines pulled up

989
01:03:17,669 --> 01:03:19,592
and we were sure
that they weren't for us.

990
01:03:19,713 --> 01:03:22,557
We were like kind of
walking around them.

991
01:03:22,549 --> 01:03:25,223
Like, "Oh, we better get out
of these people's way

992
01:03:25,343 --> 01:03:27,721
"'cause they're important people
in limos".

993
01:03:27,721 --> 01:03:30,725
But they were for us.
And that's when it began.

994
01:03:30,724 --> 01:03:34,729
<i>It was all another world.
It was another world.</i>

995
01:03:34,853 --> 01:03:40,075
<i>(Eva) Just like you would see people...
over Madonna or...</i>

996
01:03:40,191 --> 01:03:45,618
Like stepping out into the wind
and the paparazzi and all the...

997
01:03:45,613 --> 01:03:51,586
you know, the production assistants
and everybody are there to welcome him

998
01:03:51,703 --> 01:03:54,923
and take us into the VIP suite.

999
01:03:55,040 --> 01:03:59,261
<i>(Regan) The white carpeting.
You know, that was something that

1000
01:03:59,252 --> 01:04:03,803
never would we ever even dream
of walking on white carpeting,

1001
01:04:03,923 --> 01:04:05,971
especially in your shoes. (laughs)

1002
01:04:06,760 --> 01:04:09,479
<i>(Segerman) They put him in a limo
and they drove him into the city.</i>

1003
01:04:09,471 --> 01:04:14,318
<i>And along the way, on all the lampposts,
were placards advertising the concert.</i>

1004
01:04:14,392 --> 01:04:17,271
And he saw his face on every lamppost
as it sped by

1005
01:04:17,270 --> 01:04:19,819
and he'd go,
"There I am, there I am, there I am".

1006
01:04:19,939 --> 01:04:22,818
<i>(Eva) So we came
and we got to meet all the people.</i>

1007
01:04:22,817 --> 01:04:26,617
<i>We got to meet Craig Bartholomew
and their family and their kids</i>

1008
01:04:26,613 --> 01:04:28,615
<i>and Stephen Segerman.</i>

1009
01:04:28,740 --> 01:04:32,461
And everybody was just so happy.
Everybody was thrilled.

1010
01:04:32,452 --> 01:04:33,920
We were even happier.

1011
01:04:34,454 --> 01:04:35,831
<i>(Möller) Stephen phoned me.

1012
01:04:35,830 --> 01:04:38,174
<i>He said, "You will never believe this...

1013
01:04:39,459 --> 01:04:41,632
"but Rodriguez is coming to South Africa

1014
01:04:41,628 --> 01:04:43,471
"and we can be the opening band.

1015
01:04:43,463 --> 01:04:47,093
"Do you wanna do it?"
I said, "Of course we wanna do it".

1016
01:04:48,426 --> 01:04:51,475
"Why? Where is he?"
"Now they found him.

1017
01:04:51,596 --> 01:04:55,146
"They found him, he's alive, he's gonna
come and tour in South Africa".

1018
01:04:55,141 --> 01:04:59,317
"Are we gonna be the opening band?"
So I couldn't really believe this.

1019
01:05:00,814 --> 01:05:05,490
And then I got all the information:
he's living in Detroit and everything.

1020
01:05:05,485 --> 01:05:07,203
And then a little while later he said,

1021
01:05:07,195 --> 01:05:09,823
"Look, it turns out
he hasn't got a band.

1022
01:05:09,948 --> 01:05:13,498
"Could we be the support band?"
I mean his band.

1023
01:05:14,452 --> 01:05:18,002
I remember, even then, we were sort of,

1024
01:05:19,499 --> 01:05:21,376
"Is this really gonna be Rodriguez?"

1025
01:05:21,376 --> 01:05:24,004
We'll only know
if he can actually sing these songs.

1026
01:05:24,129 --> 01:05:27,383
I mean, we don't know.
What if it's just some guy? (chuckles)

1027
01:05:27,882 --> 01:05:29,008
<i>(Sandra) It was just like</i>

1028
01:05:29,134 --> 01:05:30,351
<i>one day we heard about it</i>

1029
01:05:30,343 --> 01:05:32,641
<i>and the next day we were there,

1030
01:05:34,013 --> 01:05:35,856
<i>trying to believe our eyes,</i>

1031
01:05:35,974 --> 01:05:38,853
<i>thinking it was just all very shocking.</i>

1032
01:05:38,977 --> 01:05:41,196
<i>I don't know, he took to it really easy.</i>

1033
01:05:41,187 --> 01:05:43,565
<i>He just walked in and did his thing</i>

1034
01:05:43,565 --> 01:05:47,195
<i>and I was amazed that he did so well.</i>

1035
01:05:47,193 --> 01:05:48,194
<i>But he's not all</i>

1036
01:05:48,319 --> 01:05:49,366
<i>"head in the clouds" kinda guy.</i>

1037
01:05:49,487 --> 01:05:53,208
<i>He's a little bit too much grounded.</i>

1038
01:05:53,283 --> 01:05:54,910
<i>He didn't take advantage</i>

1039
01:05:54,909 --> 01:05:57,037
<i>of all the amenities and stuff.</i>

1040
01:05:57,120 --> 01:05:59,919
He didn't sleep in the big
double king size bed.

1041
01:05:59,914 --> 01:06:03,760
He kinda curled up on the love seat
and I found him there and...

1042
01:06:03,751 --> 01:06:07,255
Yeah, he just didn't think somebody
should have to make another bed

1043
01:06:07,255 --> 01:06:09,257
because he messed it up or...

1044
01:06:09,257 --> 01:06:10,634
<i>(Regan) There was a time</i>

1045
01:06:10,717 --> 01:06:12,765
<i>where I stayed in the house we were at</i>

1046
01:06:12,886 --> 01:06:15,389
<i>and everyone else had gone out.</i>

1047
01:06:15,472 --> 01:06:17,099
<i>The phone rang and it kept ringing,</i>

1048
01:06:17,223 --> 01:06:19,317
<i>so I decided to answer it.</i>

1049
01:06:19,392 --> 01:06:20,769
<i>And it was a reporter

1050
01:06:20,894 --> 01:06:22,737
looking to speak with Rodriguez

1051
01:06:22,812 --> 01:06:25,782
and set up time for an interview.

1052
01:06:26,483 --> 01:06:31,284
And then, before she hung up,
after I told her to call back later

1053
01:06:31,279 --> 01:06:33,657
to talk to someone
'cause I couldn't help her,

1054
01:06:33,740 --> 01:06:38,337
she told me that she wanted to know,
between she and I,

1055
01:06:38,411 --> 01:06:40,334
if it was the real Rodriguez.

1056
01:06:40,413 --> 01:06:41,915
(indistinct chatter)

1057
01:06:42,999 --> 01:06:45,297
<i>(Möller) We were rehearsing with a CD

1058
01:06:45,293 --> 01:06:47,512
<i>of the songs that we've got

1059
01:06:47,504 --> 01:06:48,926
<i>in the studio here in Cape Town

1060
01:06:49,005 --> 01:06:52,475
on the day that he came
from the airport, when he arrived,

1061
01:06:52,467 --> 01:06:56,142
and we were actually in the middle
of a song when he walked in

1062
01:06:56,262 --> 01:06:58,936
and just took over the microphone
and finished the song.

1063
01:06:59,015 --> 01:07:01,484
We switched off the CD player

1064
01:07:01,476 --> 01:07:04,320
and it was, like, completely seamless.

1065
01:07:04,312 --> 01:07:05,689
<i>Completely seamless.</i>

1066
01:07:05,772 --> 01:07:07,945
<i>I mean, "OK, this is the guy".</i>

1067
01:07:08,024 --> 01:07:09,822
<i>I think we all knew this is</i>

1068
01:07:09,817 --> 01:07:11,945
<i>gonna be something really special.</i>

1069
01:07:29,963 --> 01:07:32,637
<i>Thank you, Cape Town. Thank you.</i>

1070
01:07:34,509 --> 01:07:35,556
<i>(Regan) When we, uh...</i>

1071
01:07:35,635 --> 01:07:36,727
<i>initially got on a plane,</i>

1072
01:07:36,803 --> 01:07:38,851
<i>I thought maybe there'd be, hopefully,</i>

1073
01:07:38,846 --> 01:07:41,065
<i>20 people in the audience.</i>

1074
01:07:41,516 --> 01:07:42,893
Hopefully. (laughs)

1075
01:07:44,185 --> 01:07:47,064
But it turned out really,
really different than that.

1076
01:07:47,188 --> 01:07:49,987
And there's old people and young people

1077
01:07:50,066 --> 01:07:53,161
and they're coming to see the show.

1078
01:07:53,236 --> 01:07:57,241
<i>And there's my step-dad on the stage...
Before he went on stage,</i>

1079
01:07:57,323 --> 01:07:59,417
<i>'cause I wanted to take
a picture of the audience,</i>

1080
01:07:59,492 --> 01:08:01,494
<i>since nobody's gonna believe this.</i>

1081
01:08:01,578 --> 01:08:03,046
<i>(Bartholomew-Strydom)
You must remember, this guy,</i>

1082
01:08:03,037 --> 01:08:06,086
<i>it's like seeing someone like Elvis
come back from the dead.</i>

1083
01:08:06,207 --> 01:08:07,675
<i>People in the audience
still don't believe it.</i>

1084
01:08:07,750 --> 01:08:09,593
